open
The open command lets you open a file using this syntax:

Bash
open <filename>
You can also open a directory, which on macOS opens the Finder app with the current directory open:

Bash
open <directory name>
I use it all the time to open the current directory:

(Note: The rest of the command string at the very bottom is cut off, but the standard way to do this is open .)

💡 Cross-Platform Alternatives for open
The open command shown here is highly specific to macOS for launching applications or opening Finder windows. If you switch environments, the exact equivalent changes:

Linux (Ubuntu/Debian, etc.): Use xdg-open instead of open. For example, opening the current folder in your graphical file manager would be:

Bash
xdg-open .
Windows (PowerShell/CMD): Use the start command. For example, opening the current folder in File Explorer would be:

Bash
start .